'''Public health nursing''', a term coined by [[Lillian Wald]] of the [[Henry Street Settlement]], or '''community health nursing''', is a [[nursing]] specialty focused on [[public health]].  Public health nurses (PHNs) or community health nurses "integrate community involvement and knowledge about the entire population with personal, clinical understandings of the health and illness experiences of individuals and families within the population."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apha.org/membergroups/sections/aphasections/phn/ |title=Public Health Nursing Section |publisher=APHA |date=2012-05-15 |accessdate=2012-11-30}}</ref>  Public health nursing in the United States traces back to a nurse named [[Lillian Wald]] who, in 1893, established the [[Henry Street Settlement]] in New York City and coined the expression "public health nurse".

Public health nurses work within communities and focus on different areas to improve the overall health of the people within that community. Some areas of employment for public health nurses are school districts, county or state health departments, and departments of correction. The public health nurse looks for areas of concern within the community and assesses and plans ways through which the concerns can be resolved or minimized. Some health concerns a public health nurse may work on are infection control, health maintenance, health coaching, as well as home care visits for welfare and to provide care to certain members of the community who may need it.

